{
  "sectionCode": "131",
  "sectionCodeDisplay": "131",
  "title": "The Cosmos 5",
  "outline": [
    {
      "level": "A",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "The structure and properties of the universe",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Basic data for the universe",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The estimated chemical composition of the universe [see also 121.D.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The large-scale structure and behaviour of the universe: evidence that the universe is expanding, Hubble's law and the theory of the red shift",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The age of the universe",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The clustering of galaxies",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Cosmic microwave background radiation",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "f",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The missing mass problem",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "g",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Space-time: a four-dimensional continuum used to describe the universe",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Cosmological models: theoretical representations of the original behaviour of the universe [see E.I., below]",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The known and postulated components of the universe",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Distant galaxies [see 132. A.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The Local Group of galaxies [see 132.A.1.C.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Quasars and related objects, including such hypothetical phenomena as supermassive black holes at the centres of galaxies",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Nebulae",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Stars and stellar groups [see 132.C. and 132.D.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "f",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Planetary systems: solar and extrasolar systems [see also 133.A.]",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "B",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Gravitation: a universal force of mutual attraction that is postulated as acting between all matter",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Development of gravitational theory",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Early concepts: the Aristotelian viewpoint, contributions of Kepler and Galileo",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Newton's law of gravity [see also 126.A.3.b.v.]",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Interpretation of gravity measurements",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Potential theory: mathematical representation of the gravitational fields of irregular mass distributions [see also 10/22. D.2.C.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Effects of local mass differences: measurement of small gravity anomalies",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Modem gravitational theory and its relation to other aspects of physical theory",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Field theories of gravity and their general properties and predictions",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Gravitational fields and the general theory of relativity: principles and consequences [see D.2., below]",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Acceleration of gravity on the Earth's surface [see 212.A.]",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The gravitational constant, G: methods of measurement, possible variation in time and space",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "C",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Celestial mechanics [see 126.B]",
      "children": []
    },
    {
      "level": "D",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Properties of the space-time continuum: the astronomical implications of relativity theory",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The special theory of relativity",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Historical background: the search for the ether",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Relativity of space and time",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Consequences of the special theory",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The general theory of relativity",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Use of relativity to interpret gravitational phenomena",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Experimental confirmation of the theory",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Implications of general relativity",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "E",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "The origin and development of the universe",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The development of the universe as a whole",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Big-bang versus steady-state models of the universe",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Primordial nucleosynthesis",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The early universe: extrapolations backward in time to the beginning of the universe",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The formation and development of components of the universe: galaxies, stars, the solar system [see also 132.B., 132.D., and 133.A.]",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The origin and development of galaxies: protogalaxies",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The formation and development of stars",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The origin of the solar system",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Time scale of the universe: dating of significant events in the history of the universe",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    }
